pdc_describe.title: Updating DOI code to utilize prefix environment variables

comments.body: @carolyncole Thank you so much for this. I made a few changes to the PR so that it handles errors properly (the fancy `.either` syntax was not really working) and added special clause to work in development without credentials. I deployed it to staging and it works OK.
Coveralls does not show any decrease in the test coverage (however, the API seems to be slow)
Closed by https://github.com/pulibrary/pdc_describe/pull/180

@hectorcorrea This documentation for creating a DOI via Fabrica/Datacite appears to show that only 10.1 resourceTypeGeneral is required on the form. See: https://support.datacite.org/docs/field-descriptions-for-form

Here are some examples of the [XML code from the Datacite 4.4 help](https://support.datacite.org/docs/datacite-metadata-schema-v44-xml-metadata-examples) (note: I put weird spaces between characters, so Github wouldn't render to regular text.):

Example software:
< resourceType resourceTypeGeneral ="Software" >Software < /resourceType >

Example a simple dataset:
< resourceType resourceTypeGeneral = "Dataset" >Dataset < /resourceType >

Example for video as ResourceType:
< resourceType resourceTypeGeneral = "Audiovisual" > narrated video </resourceType> 

Example for a workflow ResourceType:
< resourceType resourceTypeGeneral = "Workflow" > Software < /resourceType >

@hectorcorrea Looking at the examples for software and a simple dataset, we might simply duplicate what is chosen from the controlled list (10.1 resourceTypeGeneral) to the free text box (10 resourceType) and only let the admin/curator change the free text (10 resourceType), as may be needed in some cases. What do you think?

This does need to be required for our purposes, so ok to put in the required section. Otherwise users won't know the extent for which they may reuse the deposit.

Your list is good to start with. Creative Commons has more than one choice, so here are all of the [CC licenses](https://creativecommons.org/about/cclicenses/):
- CC By
- CC By-SA
- CC By-NC
- CC By-NC-SA
- CC By-ND
- CC By-NC-ND
- CC0

I wonder if Creative Commons might be listed with these as subcategories and default to CC By 4.0 or CC0? This is another detail we can bring to the group.
